09/05/2003
BELGRADE, Serbia-Montenegro -- On Thursday (8 May), Serbian Prime Minister Zoran Zivkovic flatly denied media speculation about a government reshuffle, saying the cabinet was only assembled two months ago. The Belgrade daily <I>Vecernje Novosti</I> reported there are plans to dismiss Serbian Agriculture Minister Dragan Veselinov. Zivkovic also denied rumours that Vladimir "Baby" Popovic, head of the government's communications bureau, would step down.
In other news Thursday, Serbian officials handed over to the UN the remains of 37 ethnic Albanian victims of the 1999 conflict in Kosovo. They were among 1,000 bodies discovered in several areas in Serbia after the fall of the Milosevic regime. Also Thursday, Russia announced it would pull out its 1,000 troops from Kosovo and Bosnia and Herzegovina by 1 August, explaining the main problems -- trafficking and illegal immigration -- are better handled by police. (Beta, B92, Tanjug, BBC, AP, AFP - 08/05/03)
